<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A HARD-LINE STANCE ON GREECE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Greece has until 6 p.m. E.D.T. on Tuesday to make a 1.6 billion euro, or $1.8 billion, payment to the International Monetary Fund, but in an interview on state television on Monday night, the Greek prime minister, Alexis Tsipras, strongly suggested that Greece would not make that payment, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/world/europe/european-leaders-insist-greek-deal-is-still-possible.html"> Andrew Higgins and Alison Smale write in The New York Times</a>. Late Monday, Jean-Claude Juncker, the head of the European Unionâs executive branch, offered Mr. Tsipras a <b> last-minute proposal</b> that presented the possibility of a concession on demands for cuts in bonus payments for the poorest pensioners, European officials said. In return, Mr. Tsipras would have to accept all of the other creditorsâ demands, which he had already turned down, and request an emergency meeting of eurozone finance ministers on Tuesday. So far, Mr. Tsipras has not responded publicly.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Greece and its creditors dig into their respective positions, politicians and investors are trying to determine which side is bluffing, the Greeks or the European Union. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/business/dealbook/the-hard-line-on-greece.html"> In the DealBook column</a>, Andrew Ross Sorkin says that a major clue can be found in Timothy F. Geithnerâs memoir, âStress Test: Reflections on Financial Crises.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In July 2012, when Mr. Geithner was the United States Treasury secretary, he had a conversation about Greece with Wolfgang SchÃ¤uble, Germanyâs finance minister. âHe told me there were many in Europe who still thought <b> kicking the Greeks out of the eurozone was a plausible â even desirable â strategy</b>,â Mr. Geithner wrote. âThe idea was that with Greece out, Germany would be more likely to provide the financial support the eurozone needed because the German people would <b> no longer perceive aid to Europe as a bailout for the Greeks</b>.â Mr. SchÃ¤uble also told Mr. Geithner that a Greek exit from the eurozone would also be traumatic enough to <b> scare the rest of Europe </b> into working toward a stronger fiscal union. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The European Central Bankâs decision to halt an expansion of its emergency lending facility to Greece was telling, Mr. Sorkin writes. The decision may have had its financial merits, but it also served <b> a political purpose</b>, he writes: âBy closing the cash spigot, the E.C.B. managed to <b> instill additional fear and panic</b> into the day-to-day lives of the Greek people, ahead of the vote on the referendum.â Shortly after the E.C.B.âs decision, Greek imposed capital controls, which are threatening the functioning of an already impaired Greek economy, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/business/dealbook/monetary-controls-in-greece-squeeze-consumers-and-businesses.html"> Jack Ewing and Landon Thomas Jr. write in DealBook</a>. Some analysts and investors say the restrictions on money transfers may put Greece on a <b> quicker path out of the eurozone</b>. âWhile youâve got no payment system, businesses are going to struggle badly,â said Gabriel Sterne, head of Global Macro Research at Oxford Economics in London, who estimates that gross domestic product could decline by 10 percent. âMy view is, <b> you head toward the exit faster than anyone imagines</b>.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Tsipras and European leaders disagree on whether the referendum that the Greek prime minister scheduled for Sunday is tantamount to a vote on staying in the eurozone. But <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/world/europe/greek-premiers-referendum-call-tests-his-power-and-conviction.html"> Jim Yardley writes in The New York Times</a> that if nothing else, Mr. Tsiprasâs tactic remains âan audacious maneuver, defining him as a rare unpredictable force among European Union leaders, while also focusing new attention on Europeâs austerity policies and <b> highlighting the failings in the long-running Greece negotiations</b>.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After broadly falling on Monday, stock markets in Asia and Europe were steadier on Tuesday. The current <b> lack of utter panic in the markets</b> indicates that investors are betting that the situation in Greece wonât lead to the disintegration of the eurozone, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/upshot/why-arent-the-markets-freaking-out-more-about-the-greek-crisis.html"> Neil Irwin writes in The Upshot</a>. Or there could be another reason, he says: âMaybe the entities that would normally be betting that a Greek crisis would spiral into something more dangerous on Monday were out of the game, <b> either gun-shy after the last few years or broke</b>.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>FEW CURES FOR HEAVY DEBT LOADS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Like Greece, huge debt burdens are weighing heavily on governments around the world, with no easy solution available, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/business/dealbook/trillions-spent-but-crises-like-greeces-persist.html"> Peter Eavis writes in DealBook</a>. The globally significant economies of Brazil, Turkey, Italy and China are getting bogged down by high borrowing, and economists say that central banks and their stimulus programs can only go so far. â<b> Monetary policy can only be a palliative</b>,â said Diana Choyleva, chief economist at Lombard Street Research. âIt cannot be a cure.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Debt relief would be one way to lighten the load on countries, but <b> lenders arenât always willing to cooperate</b>, as in the case of Ukraine. Some of the countryâs creditors, like Franklin Templeton, an American investment firm, have <b> resisted Ukraineâs demand they take a loss</b> on their principal investment, preferring instead to extend the repayment period even as Ukraine threatens to default on its debt.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>MUTED RESPONSE TO PUERTO RICOâS DEBT CRISIS </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Though Puerto Ricoâs governor said the commonwealth would not be able to pay its $72 billion in debt, the response from the White House was relatively reserved on Monday, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/business/dealbook/puerto-ricos-bonds-drop-on-governors-warning-about-debt.html"> Michael Corkery and Mary Williams Walsh write in The New York Times</a>. The White House made it clear that Puerto Rico wouldnât get a federal bailout but expressed some support for a legislative effort to allow the islandâs <b> public corporations to use federal bankruptcy protections</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The price of some Puerto Rico general obligation bonds <b> fell as much as 12 percent</b>, to about 68 cents on the dollar, one of their largest declines in recent months, traders and analysts said. Bond insurersâ stocks were down as much as 23 percent. But <b> prices of most municipal bonds rose</b>, partly mirroring a rally in United States Treasury prices that was driven by the instability in Greece. Investors said the rise in prices showed that people believed that Puerto Ricoâs problems <b> would not lead to more systemic disruptions</b> in the $3.7 trillion municipal bonds market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"></p>
