<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>K.K.R. SETTLES OVER âBROKEN DEALâ EXPENSES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Securities and Exchange Commission said Monday that the private equity firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &#038; Company breached its fiduciary duty when it passed along more than $17 million in âbroken dealâ expenses to its investors, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/30/business/dealbook/kkr-settles-over-broken-deal-expenses.html"> Alexandra Stevenson writes in DealBook</a>. The regulator said that over a six-year period, until 2011, K.K.R. incurred $338 million in expenses related to unsuccessful buyouts, but instead of making its executives absorb some of those costs, the firm passed them on to the funds of their limited partners <b> without informing them</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To settle the accusations, K.K.R. has agreed to <b> pay nearly $30 million</b>. The S.E.C. is expected to announce <b> a series of similar actions against private equity firms</b> for misallocation of fees and disclosure failures over the next few months, people briefed on the agencyâs plans told Ms. Stevenson.<br />
</p>
